    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.20"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">20</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline><hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi> Jan 29, 1931</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear Neihardt:</salute> 
                    <note type="curatorial"><unclear/></note>
                </opener>
                <p>I wish I was feeling well enough to answer adequately your beautiful letter, and tell you how deeply I appreciate it. But, just at present, I am laid up with the "grippe," and can only scrawl a few lines. However, you can be assured that all you said, all your splendid words of praise, with their sympathetic understanding, went straight to my heart. You are right&#8212; George Sterling is not "poor George" now, he is rich in the heritage of magnificent poetry which he left, and walks with the exalted ones of the <unclear>Muse</unclear> on the fields of Asphodel. You are indeed fortunate in having such a fine family, such talented children, especially Hilda, who must be a wonderful little girl. Some day, perhaps, she may be a great poet like her father. I enclose the sonnet which she requested, and hope she will like it. If it is not too much trouble, I will be most grateful for a copy of the review of "The Trophies."</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Ever sincerely yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>John Myers OHara</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
